  "hash": "sha256:3f8a1c2d9e4b7f06a5c3d2e1b8f4a9c7d6e2b1f3a8c5d4e9b2f7a1c6d3e8b4f9",
  "signature": "ed25519:7a3c9f2e1b8d4a6c5f3e2d1b9a7c4f8e6d2b5a3c1f9e7d4b2a8c6f3e1d5b9a7c",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "NASA-STD-7009B",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "OpenFAST must be under version control with tagged releases, possess a documented verification test suite executed on each release, and have a traceable issue-tracking record. All simulation scripts used in this COU must be archived in a configuration-managed repository with commit hashes recorded in this package.",
      "rationale": "OpenFAST v3.4.0 is maintained by NREL under a formal open-source governance model with GitHub-based version control, automated CI/CD regression testing across 80+ unit and integration tests, and a public issue tracker. All simulation scripts for this COU are archived at commit SHA a3f8c21 in the project repository. A Gradation 3 requirement is appropriate because the simulation results feed directly into certification margin calculations for a Class I wind turbine; higher software assurance than typical research use is warranted, but full DO-178C rigor is not required for this pre-certification scoping phase."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "NASA-STD-7009B",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code verification must include at least one published peer-reviewed code-to-code comparison for aeroelastic DEL prediction and demonstration that OpenFAST reproduces analytical solutions for isolated structural and aerodynamic sub-models to within 2% for canonical test cases.",
      "rationale": "OpenFAST has been extensively verified through the IEA Wind Task 37 code comparison exercise (Rinker et al., 2020, Wind Energy) and the NREL/INNWIND.EU collaborative benchmarking effort. Isolated sub-model verification includes Bernoulli beam analytical solutions for ElastoDyn and thin-airfoil theory checks for AeroDyn. The Gradation 3 level is consistent with the maturity of the code base and the availability of multiple independent verification datasets."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "NASA-STD-7009B",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "A time-step convergence study must demonstrate that the chosen integration time step produces DEL values within 1% of a half-step solution. Blade element discretization must be assessed with at least two node densities.",
      "rationale": "Time-step sensitivity studies were performed at dt = 0.0125 s, 0.025 s, and 0.05 s. Blade root flapwise DEL varied by less than 0.4% between the 0.0125 s and 0.025 s runs; the production time step of 0.025 s was selected. Blade discretization was assessed at 20 and 40 aerodynamic nodes; DEL difference was 0.6%. Achieved level exceeds the required level, providing margin."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "NASA-STD-7009B",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Energy balance checks must confirm that total mechanical energy drift over a 600-second simulation is less than 0.1% of peak kinetic energy. Solver iteration convergence must be demonstrated with residual norms below 1e-6 for each time step.",
      "rationale": "OpenFAST uses a predictor-corrector tight-coupling scheme. Energy balance monitoring across all 120 DLC 1.1 seeds confirmed drift below 0.03%. Iteration residuals were logged and remained below 1e-7 in all cases. No divergence events were recorded."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "NASA-STD-7009B",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "An independent reviewer must inspect all input decks for consistency with the IEA 15-MW reference turbine specification document (NREL/TP-5000-75698) and confirm that wind field generation parameters conform to IEC 61400-1 Ed. 4 Annex B turbulence class IA requirements.",
      "rationale": "Input decks were reviewed by a second engineer not involved in their preparation. Discrepancies in tower shadow model parameters were identified and corrected prior to production runs. Wind field seeds were generated using TurbSim v2.0 with Kaimal spectral model, hub-height turbulence intensity 0.16 per IEC class IA, and 120 seeds per mean wind speed bin. Review sign-off is recorded in the project change log at revision R2.3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "NASA-STD-7009B",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "The model form factor for this COU is assessed at Gradation 4, reflecting the high consequence of model-form error on certification outcomes and the complex coupled aeroelastic physics governing blade root fatigue loads. OpenFAST employs a geometrically exact beam formulation in BeamDyn coupled to a blade element momentum aerodynamics model with dynamic stall via the Beddoes-Leishman model. The selection of these sub-models was deliberate: geometrically exact beams are necessary to capture large pre-bend and sweep of the IEA 15-MW blade without linearisation error; the B-L dynamic stall model has been validated against S809 pitching airfoil data and is the industry standard for fatigue-load estimation under turbulent inflow. Model form uncertainty was quantified by comparing OpenFAST DEL predictions against HAWC2 results for the same turbine under identical wind fields (Bak et al., 2022, Journal of Physics: Conference Series); the mean absolute percentage difference in flapwise DEL across all wind speed bins was 3.1%, within the 5% threshold established by the project technical authority as consistent with certification-grade analysis. The requirement for Gradation 4 is justified by the direct link between these simulation outputs and structural sizing decisions: errors in model form that systematically under-predict DELs could lead to unconservative laminate schedules with potential consequences for turbine structural integrity over the 20-year design life. All sub-model selection decisions are documented in the Model Description Report MDR-IEA15MW-OF-v2, which is incorporated by reference into this package. The aerodynamic polars were generated using XFOIL with boundary layer transition fixed at 5% chord on the suction side, consistent with the reference turbine specification, and cross-checked against CFD RANS results from DTU for three representative span stations. No significant discrepancies in lift curve slope were found below 12 degrees angle of attack. Structural damping coefficients were set per the IEA 15-MW specification (1% critical for all modes) and sensitivity of DEL to ±50% damping variation was assessed; the DEL sensitivity was less than 2%, confirming that model form uncertainty in this parameter does not materially affect the quantity of interest."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "NASA-STD-7009B",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All blade structural and aerodynamic input data must be traceable to the IEA 15-MW reference turbine public release (NREL/TP-5000-75698 v1.1). Sensitivity of flapwise DEL to ±10% variation in key inputs (blade mass distribution, chord, twist) must be documented and confirm DEL sensitivity below 5% per input.",
      "rationale": "Blade geometry, mass distribution, stiffness distribution, and aerodynamic polars were taken directly from the IEA 15-MW v1.1 public release. A one-at-a-time sensitivity study across 12 input parameters confirmed that no single input produced more than 3.8% change in flapwise DEL at rated wind speed. The most sensitive parameter was blade mass per unit length (3.8%); all others were below 2.5%."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "NASA-STD-7009B",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation test data must include blade root bending moment measurements from at least one instrumented turbine operating under conditions representative of DLC 1.1, with a minimum of 50 ten-minute records per mean wind speed bin between 5 and 15 m/s.",
      "rationale": "The 2023 field campaign provided 68 ten-minute records at 7 m/s, 74 at 9 m/s, 61 at 11 m/s, and 55 at 13 m/s hub-height mean wind speed. Strain gauges were calibrated against static load tests prior to deployment. Data quality screening removed records with sensor dropout or wind direction outside ±15 degrees of the rotor axis."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "NASA-STD-7009B",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Measured atmospheric turbulence intensity and shear profile during test records must be documented and confirmed to fall within IEC 61400-1 class IA bounds. Wind speed must be measured at hub height with a calibrated cup anemometer or sonic anemometer with uncertainty below 2%.",
      "rationale": "Meteorological mast data confirmed turbulence intensities between 0.13 and 0.19 across all wind speed bins, bracketing the IEC IA characteristic value of 0.16. Wind shear exponent averaged 0.18, consistent with the Hellmann exponent assumed in simulation. Hub-height wind speed was measured by a calibrated Thies First Class anemometer with MEASNET-traceable calibration."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "NASA-STD-7009B",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation input parameters used for validation runs must be matched to measured test conditions on a record-by-record basis for hub-height mean wind speed, turbulence intensity, and wind shear exponent. Matching tolerance must be within 5% for each parameter.",
      "rationale": "For each of the 258 validation records, a corresponding OpenFAST simulation was generated using measured hub-height mean wind speed, turbulence intensity, and shear exponent as inputs. Matching was achieved within 3% for all three parameters in 94% of records; the remaining 6% were excluded from the quantitative comparison."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "NASA-STD-7009B",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulated flapwise DEL must agree with measured DEL to within 10% mean absolute percentage error across all wind speed bins. Edgewise DEL agreement must be within 15%. A formal uncertainty quantification accounting for measurement uncertainty must be reported.",
      "rationale": "Flapwise DEL MAPE was 6.3% across all wind speed bins; edgewise DEL MAPE was 11.7%. Measurement uncertainty in the strain gauge system was estimated at ±3.5% (k=2). After accounting for measurement uncertainty, the simulation-to-test agreement is within the established thresholds at all wind speed bins. Bland-Altman analysis confirmed no systematic bias with wind speed."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "NASA-STD-7009B",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The validation QoI (blade root bending moment DEL) must be the same physical quantity used in the COU design calculation, or a formally justified surrogate. The Wöhler exponent used in DEL computation must match the material S-N curve exponent used in the fatigue analysis.",
      "rationale": "The validation QoI is blade root flapwise and edgewise bending moment DEL computed with Wöhler exponent m=10, consistent with the GFRP material S-N curves specified in the blade root laminate design calculation. No surrogate QoI is used; the validation directly exercises the quantity that drives the design decision."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "NASA-STD-7009B",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The validation turbine must be of comparable scale and rotor solidity to the IEA 15-MW reference turbine, operating under wind conditions representative of IEC class IA. Any scale or configuration differences must be assessed for their effect on the dominant physics and documented in a formal applicability argument.",
      "rationale": "The validation campaign was conducted on a 13-MW prototype turbine with 110 m rotor radius, representing a 93% geometric scale relative to the IEA 15-MW 120 m radius. An applicability argument documented in Applicability Report AR-2023-04 confirms that the dominant fatigue load mechanisms (turbulent inflow-driven stochastic loading, tower shadow, and gravitational edgewise loading) are preserved at this scale. Reynolds number effects on aerodynamic polars were assessed and found to affect DEL by less than 1.5%."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/wind-turbine-blade-fatigue-dlc11-cou1-decision",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nrel-credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "All thirteen NASA-STD-7009B credibility factors have been assessed. Required levels are met or exceeded for all factors. The overall credibility of the OpenFAST DLC 1.1 fatigue DEL simulation is judged sufficient to support blade root laminate sizing and certification margin assessment for the IEA 15-MW reference wind turbine. The model form factor, which carries the highest required level (Gradation 4) reflecting the consequence of model-form error on structural sizing, achieves its required level and is supported by quantitative code-to-code comparison and field validation evidence. No weakeners have been identified that would reduce the credibility assessment below the required threshold.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
